  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most countries around the world, including China. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money, or \"dirty money,\" appear to come from legitimate sources. The practice is criminalized because it undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates organized crime, corruption, and tax evasion, and poses significant risks to economic stability.\n\nIn China, the legal framework to combat money laundering is robust and continuously evolving. The **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, enacted in 2007 and revised subsequently, serves as the cornerstone of the country's efforts to combat this crime. Additionally, China has established regulatory bodies such as the People's Bank of China and the China Anti-Money Laundering Monitoring and Analysis Center to oversee and enforce compliance.\n\nChina also actively participates in international anti-money laundering initiatives and cooperates with global organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) to strengthen its legal and regulatory mechanisms. Violations of anti-money laundering laws in China can result in severe penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and confiscation of assets.\n\nOverall, money laundering is unequivocally prohibited under Chinese law, reflecting the country's commitment to maintaining financial integrity and combating criminal activities.",
